---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="fail2zig · manifesto"
  description="Why host intrusion prevention gets a next-generation rebuild, and what we believe about security tooling."
  activeNav="/manifesto"
>
  <article class="mani">
    <div class="mani-meta">
      <span>Manifesto &middot; <strong>v1.0</strong></span>
      <span>Author &middot; <strong>ul0gic</strong></span>
      <span>Published &middot; <strong>2026-02-13</strong></span>
      <span>Reading &middot; <strong>4 min</strong></span>
    </div>

    <h1>Your security tool shouldn't be <span class="hl">the vulnerability.</span></h1>
    <p class="dek">
      An argument for why host intrusion prevention gets a next-generation rebuild, and why now.
    </p>

    <h2 data-num="01">The state of things</h2>
    <p>
      Fail2ban is excellent software. It has protected more servers than almost anything else
      running on the public internet. It is also a <strong
        >20-year-old Python codebase running as root</strong
      >, parsing attacker-controlled input through the CPython interpreter, with the entire standard
      library and a chain of C extensions sitting inside its trusted computing base.
    </p>
    <p>This was a reasonable trade-off in 2005. It is an unreasonable trade-off in 2026.</p>

    <h2 data-num="02">What changed</h2>
    <p>Three things.</p>
    <p class="quiet">
      <em>One.</em> Attack traffic grew. A modest VPS today sees volumes that, a decade ago, would have
      been considered targeted. The log-parsing throughput that fail2ban was designed for is no longer
      the ceiling &mdash; it is the floor, and a lot of servers are below it.
    </p>
    <p class="quiet">
      <em>Two.</em> The deployment surface diversified. Distroless containers. Scratch images. Hardened
      minimal servers. OpenWrt routers. FreeBSD jails. Embedded Linux. None of these tolerate a Python
      runtime. Their operators have no good option for host IPS, and so they run none.
    </p>
    <p class="quiet">
      <em>Three.</em> The kernel caught up. eBPF/XDP means we can now drop hostile packets at the NIC
      driver before they touch the TCP stack &mdash; something architecturally impossible when fail2ban
      was designed. The bar for what "banning an IP" means moved, and the next generation of tooling needs
      to reach it.
    </p>

    <div class="pull">
      A security daemon that runs as root should have <span class="hl"
        >a trusted computing base you can read in an afternoon.</span
      >
    </div>

    <h2 data-num="03">What we believe</h2>

    <div class="tenets">
      <div class="row">
        <span class="n">T.01</span><span class="t"
          >The binary is the TCB.<span
            >No interpreter, no VM, no dynamic code loading. What you audit is what runs in
            production.</span
          ></span
        >
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <span class="n">T.02</span><span class="t"
          >Every allocation is explicit.<span
            >An attacker who can write a log line cannot cause an allocation they didn't pay for.</span
          ></span
        >
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <span class="n">T.03</span><span class="t"
          >Memory has a ceiling.<span
            >Not a target. Not a recommendation. A hard, configurable ceiling the daemon will never
            exceed.</span
          ></span
        >
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <span class="n">T.04</span><span class="t"
          >Dependencies are a liability.<span
            >Zero third-party packages in the critical path. C interop only for stable, audited
            kernel ABIs.</span
          ></span
        >
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <span class="n">T.05</span><span class="t"
          >Local-first, cloud-optional.<span
            >Your security posture should not depend on a vendor's uptime. Gossip, don't phone home.</span
          ></span
        >
      </div>
      <div class="row">
        <span class="n">T.06</span><span class="t"
          >Migration is the adoption path.<span
            ><code>--import-config</code> reads your fail2ban tree. Your config is ours. Your mental model
            carries over.</span
          ></span
        >
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 data-num="04">What we are not</h2>
    <p>
      fail2zig is not a WAF. It does not inspect request bodies. It is not a SIEM &mdash; it does
      not aggregate, store, or correlate logs. It is not a replacement for your network firewall or
      your cloud security groups. <strong>It has exactly one job:</strong> watch logs, decide who is attacking
      you, tell your firewall to drop their packets. Done well, with a small footprint, and without becoming
      part of the attack surface itself.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
      Comparisons to log processors, to observability platforms, to cloud-centric threat feeds
      &mdash; all off-target. fail2zig is a single binary you scp to a server and forget about.
    </blockquote>

    <h2 data-num="05">What we owe you</h2>
    <p>
      Reproducible builds. Signed binaries. Public threat model. Continuous fuzz testing. An
      external security audit before 1.0. Responsive disclosure. A changelog that tells the truth
      about what changed and why. Clear statements about what we haven't mitigated yet.
    </p>
    <p>
      Those aren't features. Those are the minimum for this category, and they are non-negotiable.
    </p>

    <h2 data-num="06">What comes next</h2>
    <p>
      Ship Phase 1. Prove the drop-in replacement &mdash; fast, correct, safe, small. Earn trust in
      production. Then: eBPF/XDP ban execution at the NIC. Encrypted gossip for distributed ban
      sharing across a fleet. Hot-reload config. Privilege separation. Adaptive thresholds that
      understand what normal looks like at 3am on a Tuesday versus 4pm on a Black Friday.
    </p>
    <p>
      The list is not short. The order is not negotiable. The first release has to stand on its own
      before any of the rest matters.
    </p>

    <div class="pull">
      If a server's last line of defense is running <span class="hl"
        >an interpreter on attacker input,</span
      > the next generation should do better.
    </div>

    <div class="sign-off">
      <div>
        <div class="who">&mdash; ul0gic</div>
        <div style="color:var(--fg-mute);margin-top:4px">Oakland &middot; February 2026</div>
      </div>
      <div class="sig">~ul0gic/</div>
    </div>

    <div
      style="display:flex;gap:10px;margin-top:48px;padding-top:32px;border-top:1px solid var(--line-soft)"
    >
      <a href="/" class="btn ghost">&larr; Overview</a>
      <a href="/security" class="btn">Read the threat model &rarr;</a>
      <a
        href="https://github.com/ul0gic/fail2zig"
        class="btn primary"
        style="margin-left:auto"
        rel="noopener noreferrer">&#9733; Star on GitHub</a
      >
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .mani {
    max-width: 880px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 96px 32px 48px;
  }
  .mani-meta {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
    display: flex;
    gap: 20px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
    padding-bottom: 20px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
  }
  .mani-meta strong {
    color: var(--fg);
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .mani h1 {
    font-size: clamp(44px, 5.5vw, 72px);
    margin-bottom: 32px;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
  }
  .mani h1 .hl {
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }
  .mani .dek {
    font-size: 22px;
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    line-height: 1.4;
    margin-bottom: 56px;
    max-width: 32ch;
    text-wrap: balance;
  }

  .mani h2 {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 14px;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
    margin: 48px 0 16px;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 40px 1fr;
    gap: 16px;
    align-items: baseline;
  }
  .mani h2::before {
    content: attr(data-num);
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .mani p {
    font-size: 18px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--fg);
    max-width: 62ch;
    margin: 0 0 20px;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  .mani p.quiet {
    color: var(--fg-dim);
  }
  .mani p strong {
    font-weight: 500;
    color: var(--fg);
    background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--accent-ghost) 60%, transparent);
    padding: 1px 4px;
  }
  .mani blockquote {
    margin: 32px 0;
    padding: 0 0 0 24px;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--accent);
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 16px;
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 56ch;
  }

  .mani .pull {
    font-size: 30px;
    line-height: 1.25;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--fg);
    max-width: 24ch;
    margin: 48px 0;
    padding: 24px 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    text-wrap: balance;
  }
  .mani .pull .hl {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .mani .tenets {
    border: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    margin: 40px 0;
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 14px;
  }
  .mani .tenets .row {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 80px 1fr;
    gap: 24px;
    padding: 18px 24px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
  }
  .mani .tenets .row:last-child {
    border-bottom: none;
  }
  .mani .tenets .row .n {
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .mani .tenets .row .t {
    color: var(--fg);
    font-weight: 500;
  }
  .mani .tenets .row .t span {
    display: block;
    color: var(--fg-dim);
    font-weight: 400;
    margin-top: 3px;
  }

  .sign-off {
    margin-top: 72px;
    padding-top: 32px;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line-soft);
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--fg-mute);
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: baseline;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 20px;
  }
  .sign-off .who {
    color: var(--fg);
  }
  .sign-off .sig {
    font-size: 28px;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-style: italic;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  @media (max-width: 700px) {
    .mani {
      padding: 48px 20px;
    }
    .mani p {
      font-size: 16px;
    }
    .mani .pull {
      font-size: 22px;
    }
    .mani h2 {
      grid-template-columns: 32px 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
